# Clean Code Rules

## Priority

- Treat every rule as MUST unless marked otherwise
- Prefer readability, maintainability, correctness over cleverness
- Optimize for the next human reader
- Apply the Boy Scout Rule: leave touched code cleaner than found

## Naming

- Use intention-revealing names
- Avoid abbreviations unless domain-standard
- One word per concept across the codebase
- Classes = nouns; functions = verbs

## Functions

- Keep functions small, doing one thing
- One level of abstraction per function
- Minimize parameters; avoid boolean flags
- Eliminate hidden side effects
- Separate commands from queries

## Comments

- Improve code first, then decide if comment is needed
- Good: non-obvious intent, warnings, rationale
- Bad: redundant, obsolete, narrating code

## Error Handling

- Keep happy path readable
- Provide diagnostic context in error messages
- Prefer exceptions/result types over error codes
- Do not return null when safer model exists

## Tests

- Treat tests as production-quality code
- One main idea per test
- Fast, isolated, self-checking, deterministic
- Add tests for behavior changes and bug fixes

## Refactoring

- Small safe steps, preserve behavior
- First make it work, then make it right
- Remove duplication, dead code, misleading abstractions
- Prefer simplest design passing all tests

## Change Process

1. Understand intent and affected behavior
2. Identify simplest correct change
3. Improve names before adding comments
4. Keep edits localized
5. Add/update tests
6. Run validation
7. Review diff for readability
8. Ensure code is cleaner than before
